[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$4-15 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, multi-system-integration depth, and care-management overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is 67. Six weeks ago he had a CT scan that found a 2.3 cm mass in the upper lobe of his right lung, and over the past forty-one days he has had an appointment with his primary care physician (who ordered the original scan because of a persistent cough), an appointment with a pulmonologist (who reviewed the imaging and ordered a PET-CT), the PET-CT itself (at a different imaging center because the pulmonologist's preferred radiologist was booked out), an appointment with a thoracic surgeon (who reviewed the PET-CT and recommended a navigational bronchoscopy with biopsy), the bronchoscopy (at the hospital outpatient surgery center, which required a pre-anesthesia evaluation visit two days before), an appointment with a medical oncologist (because the pathology came back as adenocarcinoma, stage IIA based on imaging staging), an appointment with a radiation oncologist (for stereotactic body radiation therapy consultation, since David's pulmonary function was borderline for surgery), a pulmonary function test (ordered by the radiation oncologist), an appointment with a cardiologist (because David has a history of atrial fibrillation that needs to be managed around any treatment), and a tumor board review where his case was discussed by all of these specialists at once. Throughout this period, David has been receiving prescriptions for an anticoagulant adjustment, antibiotics for a post-bronchoscopy fever, an inhaler the pulmonologist added, and a referral order for genetic testing on the tumor specimen because the medical oncologist wanted to know whether David was a candidate for targeted therapy. David has also tried to schedule a follow-up appointment with his PCP (who he has been seeing for twelve years), but the PCP's first available was four weeks out, and David is not sure whether he should keep that appointment or whether he is now "an oncology patient" and his PCP is no longer central to his care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is, by any reasonable accounting, doing the work of being a patient with a complex serious illness. He has a folder. The folder has business cards from each of the specialists, the imaging reports, copies of the pathology, the radiation oncology consultation summary, three different medication lists (each of his three pharmacies has its own version, and they do not match), a fragmentary set of after-visit summaries (some printed, some emailed, some screenshotted from patient portals), and a spreadsheet his daughter started for him that lists upcoming appointments. The spreadsheet has gotten out of date; David's daughter is in another state and has been doing this in the evenings after work. David has missed one appointment because he confused the address of the imaging center with the address of the surgery center, has shown up an hour early to another because the patient portal showed the time in a different time zone, and has had a medication near-miss because the medical oncologist's office and the cardiologist's office were operating from different versions of his medication list and one of them had not seen the change the other had made. David is exhausted, scared, and frustrated. He is also, statistically, doing better at this than most patients in his situation, because he has a daughter who is helping and the cognitive resources to track most of it himself. The patients who are not doing as well are the ones we lose: missed appointments, missed referrals, prescriptions that never get filled, follow-up imaging that never gets scheduled, and the slow attrition of patients out of the care plans their specialists carefully built.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What David would have wanted, if anyone had asked him in the first week of all of this, was a person whose entire job was to know what was happening across all of his care, to keep the calendar straight, to know which specialist had made which decision and what was supposed to happen next as a result, to make sure the medication lists agreed, to confirm that the genetic-testing order had actually been placed and that the pulmonary-function test results had actually reached the radiation oncologist, to call the imaging center the day before each appointment to verify the time and address, and to be reachable when David got an after-visit summary in the patient portal that contained a phrase he did not understand. That person, if they had existed, would have been called a nurse navigator or an oncology care coordinator. They do exist. They are concentrated in academic cancer centers and large oncology practices, are a finite resource, and are typically reserved for newly-diagnosed cancer patients in active treatment. David qualifies. Many other patients in equally complex but less-archetypally-cancer situations do not: the heart-failure patient juggling cardiology, nephrology, primary care, and a heart-failure clinic; the inflammatory-bowel-disease patient managing gastroenterology, surgery, infusion therapy, and primary care; the spine-surgery patient navigating neurosurgery, pain management, physical therapy, and post-operative imaging; the post-stroke patient coordinating neurology, rehabilitation, primary care, speech therapy, occupational therapy, and a complicated mosaic of new medications and lifestyle changes. Each of these patients has the same coordination problem David has. Almost none of them get a navigator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the central problem of care coordination in the United States in 2026, and it is one of the most expensive sources of avoidable error and avoidable suffering in the entire healthcare system. The clinical knowledge for managing any single specialty's piece of David's care is well-established and broadly agreed upon. The pulmonologist knows what to do. The thoracic surgeon knows what to do. The medical oncologist knows what to do. The radiation oncologist knows what to do. The cardiologist knows what to do. What no individual specialist knows, in many real-world cases, is what the others have just decided. The information flow between specialists, between specialists and primary care, between specialists and pharmacies, between any of them and the patient, is fragmented, mediated by patient portals that do not always exchange data, by fax machines (still), by shared EHRs that work well within the academic center but not across the imaging center across town, and by patients who are expected to be the integration layer between systems that should have been integrated decades ago. The care plan, in many real cases, lives in nobody's head completely; it lives in fragments across many systems and in patients who are doing their best to hold it together.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The economics make the problem worse, not better. Care fragmentation drives substantial cost: redundant imaging, duplicate testing, medication errors, avoidable hospital readmissions, missed follow-up that turns into emergency-department visits, and outright treatment failures because pieces of the plan never executed. <!-- TODO: verify; the cost of care fragmentation and poor care transitions is documented in studies including the IOM "Crossing the Quality Chasm" reports and ongoing work by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality, the National Quality Forum, and others; specific figures vary by methodology --> Care navigators, where they exist, repeatedly demonstrate value: lower readmission rates, better treatment adherence, improved patient experience, and better outcomes for the conditions where they have been studied. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence for nurse navigation in oncology and other complex conditions includes studies showing reductions in time to treatment, reductions in care gaps, and improvements in patient-reported outcomes; specific effect sizes vary by program and population --> The reason most patients do not get navigators is the same reason most patients do not get nurse care managers: the labor model does not scale to the population that would benefit. Nurse navigators are nurses, are expensive, and are in short supply.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generation of digital care-coordination products tried to address this with patient portals and shared care plans. Patient portals, where they actually integrate across institutions, improve some pieces of the experience: patients can see their imaging reports, their lab results, their after-visit summaries. Shared care plans, where they exist as digital artifacts, can give the patient a single document with the names of their providers and the upcoming steps in their care. The clinical evidence for these tools, as care-coordination interventions, has been mixed. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for patient portals as care-coordination tools shows variable effects on adherence, missed appointments, patient experience, and clinical outcomes, with stronger effects when portals are integrated with active care-team workflows than when they are passive document repositories --> The fundamental problem these products have is that they are documents. A document does not call the imaging center the day before to confirm the time. A document does not notice that the cardiologist's medication list and the medical oncologist's medication list disagree. A document does not catch that the genetic-testing order placed by the medical oncologist three weeks ago has not been resulted yet and probably needs a phone call to the pathology lab. The work the navigator does is not document work; it is integration work, judgment work, and follow-up work. Documents alone cannot do it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2024, is that conversational AI got good enough to do meaningful pieces of the navigator's job. A conversational care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can hold the patient's care plan in working memory across all involved specialists, can ingest data from multiple source systems through API integrations and FHIR exchanges, can answer the patient's "what is supposed to happen next" questions accurately, can confirm appointment details the day before, can flag medication-list disagreements to the care team, can recognize when an ordered test has not been completed and surface it for follow-up, can warm-hand-off to a human navigator for the cases that need one, and can provide consistent between-visit support to a much larger population than the navigator workforce alone could serve. The assistant is not a navigator. The assistant is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the navigator workflow operate at population scale, with the human navigators focused on the highest-complexity cases and the AI assistant handling the substantial volume of coordination work that is genuinely automatable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that system. The care coordination assistant is the conversational AI use case where the architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes (FAQ bot, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits navigator, triage, chronic disease coach, mental health support) all converge into a single multi-system orchestration product, and where several entirely new patterns enter the picture: cross-system care-plan synthesis, multi-EHR or HIE-mediated chart context, referral and order tracking, transition-of-care management, longitudinal care-team awareness across institutional boundaries, and the kind of slow, careful, consistent follow-up work that is harder to engineer well than it looks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that helps patients navigate complex multi-specialty care episodes, with consolidated care-plan visibility, appointment and referral tracking, transition-of-care support (post-hospital, post-procedure, between specialists), medication-reconciliation flagging, between-visit education and answers grounded in the patient's specific care plan, and warm handoff to human navigators when the situation calls for it. The assistant is owned by the patient's institution (or by the network of participating institutions in a federated deployment) and operates within the boundaries of the institution's care-coordination policies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease management coach. Recipe 11.7 covers ongoing chronic-condition coaching with a longitudinal coach-patient relationship over years. The care coordination assistant addresses episode-of-care complexity (a cancer diagnosis and treatment course, a complex post-surgical recovery, a multi-specialty workup for a new diagnosis) and transition points (post-discharge, post-procedure, between-specialist handoffs). The two architectures share a great deal of plumbing and frequently coexist for patients who have both ongoing chronic conditions and episodic complex care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. The care coordination assistant handles the logistics and education around an established care plan; when a patient surfaces an acute concern that may be a complication or a new emergency (chest pain in a post-cardiac-procedure patient, fever in a recently-discharged surgical patient, severe shortness of breath in any patient), the assistant hands off to triage workflows or to direct emergency routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a diagnosis tool. The conditions the assistant is helping the patient navigate are conditions for which the patient already has a diagnostic workup or established diagnosis. The assistant does not interpret pending results, does not propose differential diagnoses, and does not advise the patient to ignore findings. When the patient surfaces questions about results or new symptoms, the assistant retrieves relevant information from the chart, supports the patient's understanding of what their care team has already documented, and routes anything outside that scope back to the care team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a primary patient-portal replacement. Most institutions already have patient portals that show appointments, results, messages, and bills. The care coordination assistant complements the portal, providing conversational access and pro-active follow-up around the same data. The two coexist; the portal is the source of truth, the assistant is the conversational navigation layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the care team. The assistant extends the care team's reach. The patient still has their primary care physician, their specialists, their nurse navigators (where they exist), their pharmacists, their care managers (where they exist), and their social workers (where they exist). The assistant handles the day-to-day logistics and education, freeing the human team to focus on clinical decisions and the genuinely complex coordination cases. The assistant is not the navigator, and the patient is told this explicitly and frequently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. The coordination needs of a newly-diagnosed cancer patient are meaningfully different from the coordination needs of a post-surgical patient, which are different from the coordination needs of a heart-failure patient with complex multi-specialty management, which are different from the coordination needs of a high-utilizer with multiple unrelated chronic conditions. Most institutions deploy a multi-condition coordination architecture with episode-specific protocols layered on a shared conversational core.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing care-coordination software, particularly when it interprets clinical content for patients, manages medication-reconciliation flags, or guides patient action around treatment plans, sits adjacent to the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's 2022 final guidance on Clinical Decision Support software addresses some patient-facing software; the regulatory positioning of care-coordination software depends on the specific functionality, the population served, and the institutional claims --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters, not sprints. The multi-system integration work is the largest piece. The clinical-content investment is multi-quarter. The care-team-workflow integration is multi-quarter. The outcome demonstration is multi-year.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the assistant's value is not in any individual conversation. The value is in the cumulative effect of consistent, accurate, multi-system integration over the duration of a complex care episode, in the navigation work the assistant does in the background (confirming appointments, surfacing missing follow-up, flagging medication disagreements), and in the early-warning signals it raises to the human navigators for the cases that need their attention. An assistant evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. An assistant evaluated on care-completion metrics (referrals closed, follow-ups completed, time-to-treatment, missed-appointment rate, medication-reconciliation flag detection rate, readmission rate, patient-reported coordination experience) is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Multi-System Care-Plan Synthesis With Conversational Navigation and Human-Navigator Backup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools For Twenty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-spreadsheet problem for decades. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires holding, in a single working memory, all of the things happening across a patient's care: which specialists are involved, what each has decided, what is supposed to happen next, what has actually happened, what is outstanding, what has gone wrong, what the patient understands and what they do not, what the medication list across all prescribers actually is, what the patient's insurance covers and what it does not for the next planned step, what the patient's transportation, financial, and social situation looks like for following through on the plan. The questions are specific to the patient's specific care episode. The questions for a newly-diagnosed cancer patient in workup are different from those for the same patient after a treatment decision has been made and treatment has begun. The questions for a post-surgical patient on day three are different from day thirty. The recommendations are episode-specific, are calibrated to where the patient is in their care journey, and depend on data scattered across multiple systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing nurse navigators do, when they do this well, is hold a longitudinal multi-system model of the patient in their heads, supplemented by chart notes, by phone calls to other offices, by faxes received and sent, by a notebook or spreadsheet of their own, and by reading their own institution's EHR alongside whatever they can pry out of other institutions. The model includes "what care plan is this patient executing across all involved specialists," "what is the current state of each step (ordered, scheduled, completed, resulted)," "what is overdue," "what is upcoming," "what does the patient know," "what is the patient confused about," "what are the patient's stated obstacles to following through," and "where are the failure points (the place the genetic-testing order has been sitting for three weeks, the cardiology appointment that was rescheduled and never re-confirmed, the prescription that has not been picked up, the post-discharge follow-up that has not been scheduled)." Holding this model is most of the cognitive work; producing the actual conversation with the patient and the actual phone calls to other offices is the easy part once the model is in place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital care-coordination products, roughly the mid-2000s through the late 2010s, tried to systematize the data part of this without the conversation part. Care-management software inside the EHR provided structured worklists for nurse navigators. Shared-care-plan documents (some standards-based, some not) tried to give multiple providers a view of a single plan. Patient portals gave patients access to some of their own data. The clinical evidence for these tools, as standalone interventions, was mixed. The fundamental problem they had was that the data integration was incomplete (cross-institution data exchange has been slow to mature, and continues to be uneven), the patient-facing surfaces were document-shaped rather than conversation-shaped, and the proactive follow-up work that is the navigator's most valuable function was not automatable with the technology available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2018 to 2023, layered analytics on top: predictive risk scores for readmission, machine-learning models for identifying high-utilizers, automated outreach systems for specific campaigns (overdue mammograms, overdue diabetic eye exams, overdue refills). The clinical evidence for some of these is meaningful, and they have improved the targeting of human navigators to the patients who need them most. The fundamental constraints, though, were similar: the patient-facing experience was still mostly portal-shaped, the conversation work still required humans, and the broad middle of patients in complex episodes still mostly had to be their own coordinators.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, accurate conversation grounded in multi-system data. A conversational care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can hold the multi-system model the navigator holds (it has the consolidated care plan, it has the cross-system data, it has the patient's history with the assistant, it has the institution's clinical content), can answer the patient's coordination questions with reliable retrieval over the consolidated context, can run the proactive follow-up tasks (appointment confirmations, medication-reconciliation checks, referral-status checks, post-discharge wellness checks) at scale, can recognize when something has gone off-plan and surface it to the human navigator, and can warm-hand-off to the human navigator for the cases that need human judgment. The LLM is not a navigator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the navigation workflow operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "static document the patient downloads" to "live conversational view of the multi-system care plan with automated follow-up and human escalation." The assistant's value is concentrated in three places: the consolidated multi-system data integration (turning fragmented data across many systems into a coherent care-plan view), the proactive follow-up automation (the boring but high-value work of confirming appointments, flagging outstanding orders, checking on post-discharge patients, reconciling medication lists), and the operational reach (extending the navigation workforce's effective coverage from the highest-acuity patients to a much larger population in complex episodes).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (consolidated care plan across all involved specialists, current medications across all prescribers, active orders and their status, upcoming appointments across all settings, recent encounters and their summaries, conversation history with the assistant), access to a structured library of institutional patient-education content, and a set of tools for retrieving cross-system data, checking referral and order status, flagging medication-reconciliation issues, scheduling and confirming appointments, sending reminders, surfacing care-team alerts, and escalating to the human navigator team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the patient (the most common pattern), sometimes initiated by the assistant per a scheduled follow-up (appointment confirmation the day before, post-discharge wellness check on day three), sometimes triggered by a data event (a specialist's office sent a new note, a pharmacy reported a refill that did not match the medication list, an order has been pending past its expected resolution window).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and care-plan introduction.** The patient is enrolled in the assistant when they enter a complex care episode (a new cancer diagnosis, a hospitalization with planned multi-specialist follow-up, a complex elective surgery, a major chronic-disease event requiring coordination across specialties). The first conversation introduces the assistant, sets expectations clearly (the assistant is a tool, not a person; it can help with logistics and information; it cannot replace the human care team; here is how to reach a human navigator), confirms the patient's understanding of their current care plan, and gathers any patient-stated preferences (preferred communication channels, language, preferred times of day, named caregiver who may participate in the conversation with the patient's consent).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consolidated care-plan visibility.** The patient can ask the assistant about their care plan ("what is supposed to happen next," "when is my next appointment," "have I had my pulmonary function test yet," "did the genetic-testing order get placed"). The assistant retrieves the relevant data from the consolidated source (FHIR ServiceRequest, Appointment, DiagnosticReport, MedicationRequest, CarePlan, and similar resources), formats the answer for the patient, and cites the source. The retrieval is grounded; the assistant does not invent or paraphrase the care plan.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment management and confirmation.** The assistant proactively confirms upcoming appointments per the institution's confirmation cadence, walks the patient through what to expect (location, parking, what to bring, what to wear, fasting or other prep requirements), and supports rescheduling when needed (handing off to the scheduling bot from recipe 11.2 for the actual booking).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral and order tracking.** The assistant tracks the status of pending referrals and orders. When the medical oncologist orders genetic testing, the assistant knows the order has been placed, knows the expected turnaround time, can answer the patient's "have we heard back yet" questions accurately, and surfaces a follow-up to the human navigator team if the order has been outstanding past the expected window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication-list reconciliation.** The assistant compares medication lists across prescribers, pharmacies, and the patient's own report. When the lists disagree, the assistant flags the discrepancy: not as a clinical decision (which medication is correct is a clinical question), but as an awareness signal for the patient and the care team. The reconciliation flag routes to the patient's primary care or to the relevant prescriber per the institution's policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transition-of-care support.** Around hospital discharge, post-procedure recovery, or specialist-to-specialist handoffs, the assistant runs structured check-ins per the institution's protocol: discharge-instruction reinforcement, medication-reconciliation, follow-up-appointment confirmation, symptom monitoring per the discharge plan, escalation when symptoms suggest a complication. The transition-of-care window is the highest-stakes period for care coordination; the assistant's value here is concentrated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated questions within scope.** The patient can ask the assistant questions about their care plan, their conditions, their medications, their upcoming steps, and (with grounded retrieval over institutional content) general questions about their conditions. The assistant answers within scope; the assistant escalates outside scope (clinical-decision questions, new acute symptoms, substantial deviations from the care plan, mental-health concerns, requests for medical advice the assistant should not provide).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Education and content delivery.** The assistant delivers patient-education content drawn from the institution's curated library at moments when it is contextually relevant: pre-procedure preparation, post-procedure recovery, condition-specific self-management, side-effect support, lifestyle modifications relevant to the care plan. The content is grounded in the institution's reviewed library.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team alert surfacing.** When the patient surfaces something the care team needs to know (a missed dose, a new symptom, a stated barrier to following through on a step), the assistant generates a structured alert with the conversation context attached, routes to the appropriate human (primary care, specialist, navigator, pharmacist), and lets the patient know the message has been sent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warm handoff to human navigators.** The assistant escalates to a human navigator when the situation calls for it: any low-confidence handling of a coordination question, any complex-care-plan-synthesis question that crosses multiple specialties, any patient request for a human, any concerning trajectory in the patient's reported state, any cross-institution coordination gap that requires phone-call work the assistant cannot do. The handoff is warm: the navigator joins with the conversation context loaded, and the assistant supports the conversation until the navigator is established.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting (with consent).** Where the patient has consented to information-sharing across their care team, the assistant generates structured summaries (weekly digests of patient-reported state, alert events for significant changes, transition-of-care summaries) for the relevant clinicians. The reports are designed for the care team's workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding when the episode resolves.** Some care episodes resolve. A surgical recovery completes. A treatment course ends. A workup completes and the patient transitions back to routine care. The assistant supports the off-boarding with structured summary delivery and a clear path back if the patient needs the assistant again.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some FAQs about referrals and appointments, and have it help the patient. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of the consolidated care plan across systems.** Care coordination is, fundamentally, a multi-system data integration problem. The patient's primary care notes are in one EHR. The cancer center's notes are in another. The imaging center's reports are in a third. The pharmacy data is in yet another. Without explicit cross-system data integration (whether through HIE participation, FHIR-based patient access APIs, or specific bilateral integrations), the LLM has no view of the full care plan and produces fragmentary, inconsistent answers based on whatever fraction of the data is wired in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no longitudinal memory of the episode.** Without a structured longitudinal store of the care episode (which orders are pending, which referrals have closed, which appointments are scheduled, which medications are active across all prescribers, what the patient has said in prior conversations), the assistant treats every conversation as a fresh start. An assistant without longitudinal episode memory is a chatbot, not a navigator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no proactive engagement architecture.** The navigator's most valuable work is proactive: calling the day before to confirm the appointment, checking on the post-discharge patient on day three, noticing that the genetic-testing order has been sitting for too long. A reactive bot that only responds when the patient initiates is missing the part of the navigation work that has the highest yield. The proactive engagement is encoded in the institution's care-coordination protocols, scheduled by the assistant's engagement layer, and triggered by data-event pipelines.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model hallucinates content when grounding is weak.** If the consolidated care plan, the institutional content library, and the cross-system data are not retrieved with strict citation grounding, the LLM produces plausible-sounding answers about the patient's care that are wrong. "Yes, your PET-CT has been scheduled" is a sentence the LLM can produce based on conversational context alone, with no actual retrieval. Strict citation grounding to authoritative source records is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-content arithmetic problems.** The clinical content used in care coordination (medication reconciliation, dose calculations, time-since-procedure rules, follow-up-window calculations) involves arithmetic on structured inputs. The LLM does this poorly. The deterministic logic (compare medication lists, calculate days-since-discharge, evaluate whether an order has been pending past its expected window) lives in tool implementations, not in the LLM's reasoning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation.** When a post-discharge patient reports chest pain, when a post-procedure patient reports a fever, when a post-surgical patient reports new severe shortness of breath, when a patient on chemotherapy reports concerning symptoms, the response is not "let me help you reschedule your follow-up." The response is to escalate to triage or directly to emergency contacts. The escalation logic is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope.** Patients in complex care episodes routinely ask the assistant questions outside its scope: "is this normal?", "what does this mean?", "should I take this medication or stop it?", "what would happen if I skipped this step?". The assistant answers within scope, escalates outside scope, and does not pretend to be a clinician. The scope discipline is encoded in prompts, in retrieval boundaries, and in output verification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications.** Care-coordination conversations contain PHI from multiple institutions, sometimes including data shared under specific consent terms that limit its use. The audit, consent, retention, and cross-institution-sharing posture has to handle these explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-institution data integrity.** Different sources may disagree about the same data point. The medical oncologist's note says the patient is on apixaban 5mg twice daily; the patient's own account says they are taking it once daily because the cardiologist changed the dose; the pharmacy data shows the most recent fill was for the once-daily dose with a recent date. Reconciling these disagreements is not a freestyle LLM task; it is a structured comparison with explicit rules for which source wins under which conditions, with the disagreement surfaced for human resolution where the rules cannot resolve it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the episode is over.** A care episode has a beginning, a middle, and an end. The assistant knows when to engage proactively, knows when to scale back, knows when to off-board the patient back to routine care. Encoding the episode lifecycle is part of the architecture, not an emergent property of the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no integration with the human navigator workflow.** The assistant's value depends on smooth handoffs to and from human navigators. The navigator's workflow tooling (case management, alert review, handoff acceptance, conversation context display) is part of the production scope. Building an assistant without navigator-side tooling produces an assistant the navigators do not trust and do not use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient understanding.** A patient who has just been told they have stage IIA lung cancer is operating at a different cognitive bandwidth than that same patient three months later when they are stable in treatment. The assistant adapts the depth, pacing, and content of its responses to where the patient is. The adaptation is part of the prompt engineering and the conversation review process.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage adaptation (from 11.7), warm handoff to licensed clinicians (from 11.8). The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system data integration as architectural primitive.** The assistant's value depends on consolidated visibility across multiple data sources: the institution's primary EHR, secondary EHRs at participating institutions, HIE-mediated data exchange, pharmacy systems, lab systems, imaging systems, and (for high-utilizer use cases) claims data. The integration layer is owned jointly by clinical informatics, IT, and the care-coordination operations team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-aware care-plan synthesis with versioning.** Each care episode has a structured representation: the involved providers, the active orders, the upcoming appointments, the active medications across all prescribers, the recent encounters, the open follow-ups. The episode representation is owned by the care-coordination service, version-controlled, and refreshed on a defined cadence as new data arrives from source systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral and order lifecycle tracking with timeout monitoring.** Each order or referral has an expected turnaround window. Orders that exceed the window without resolution generate follow-up tasks. The lifecycle states (placed, acknowledged, scheduled, completed, resulted, closed) are tracked explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication-reconciliation flag generation with structured comparison.** The assistant compares medication lists across sources and generates structured flags when disagreements exceed defined thresholds. The flags do not make clinical decisions; they surface disagreements for clinical resolution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transition-of-care protocol execution.** The institution's transition-of-care protocols (post-hospital, post-procedure, post-ED, between-specialist) are encoded as structured engagement schedules. Each protocol has named touchpoints, specified content per touchpoint, and escalation criteria. The assistant executes the protocol with patient-specific adaptation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-stakeholder reporting with consent boundaries.** The assistant generates structured outputs for multiple stakeholder roles (the patient's PCP, the patient's specialists, the institution's nurse navigators, the patient's caregiver where consented). Each stakeholder receives only the data and context their role and consent permit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-tool integration as first-class production capability.** The human navigator's worklist, alert review surface, handoff inbox, and conversation context viewer are part of production scope. The institution's case management or care coordination platform integration is operationalized.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome correlation with care-coordination metrics.** The assistant's clinical and operational performance is measured against care-coordination outcomes: missed-appointment rate, time-to-treatment for new diagnoses, referral-completion rate, transition-of-care follow-up completion, medication-reconciliation flag-rate and resolution-rate, readmission rate, patient-reported coordination experience.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The data is in many places, and many of them are not yours.** The single largest engineering investment in the assistant is the cross-system data integration. Where the patient's care is entirely within a single integrated delivery network with a single shared EHR, the integration is comparatively straightforward. Where the patient's care spans multiple institutions (most real cases for complex episodes), the integration involves HIE participation, bilateral data-exchange agreements, FHIR-based patient access APIs, and (still, in 2026) some fax-and-phone work that the assistant cannot fully automate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institutional data exchange is uneven.** The TEFCA framework and the broader HIE landscape have improved over the past several years, and the regulatory pressure to share data continues to grow. <!-- TODO: verify; the Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA) implementation has been progressing since 2022 with phased Qualified Health Information Network designations; specific coverage and capabilities continue to evolve --> Coverage is still uneven by region, by institution participation, and by data type. Imaging data is notoriously harder to exchange than text. Pharmacy data is reasonably mature. Outpatient specialty notes are inconsistent. The assistant degrades gracefully where data is missing, with explicit acknowledgment to the patient when a source is unavailable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient's understanding of their care is the operational baseline.** Patients in complex episodes routinely have an inaccurate model of their own care. They know they are supposed to see the medical oncologist next, but they think the appointment is on Tuesday when it is actually on Thursday. They know they were given a new medication, but they cannot remember the name. They know they had a scan, but they are not sure whether the results have come back. The assistant's most fundamental coordination work is keeping the patient's mental model accurate; everything else builds on that.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregivers are part of the system, formally or informally.** A meaningful fraction of complex-episode patients have a caregiver (a spouse, an adult child, a sibling) who participates in coordinating their care. The assistant's design accommodates caregiver participation under explicit consent, with structured proxy-access controls that comply with the institution's policies and applicable laws.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Health literacy varies enormously.** The assistant must adapt to patients across a wide range of health literacy without being patronizing on either end. The same content rendered for a clinician-spouse caregiver and for a patient with limited health literacy looks different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are not optional.** As with the chronic-disease coach, the populations with the highest care-coordination burden are often the populations with the most limited access to navigation services and the greatest need for culturally and linguistically appropriate support.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The financial dimension matters more than care-coordination products usually acknowledge.** Care coordination is not just clinical; it is also financial. Patients miss appointments because of transportation. Patients skip imaging because their copay was higher than expected. Patients defer follow-up because they are uncertain about coverage. The assistant integrates with the institution's financial-counseling and benefits-navigation pathways (recipe 11.5) and surfaces financial barriers to the navigator team where possible.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social determinants drive coordination outcomes.** Housing instability, food insecurity, transportation gaps, language barriers, and caregiver-availability constraints affect every step of a complex care plan. The assistant integrates with the institution's social-determinants screening and community-resources directory where they exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The assistant operates inside a workflow with humans.** The human navigator workforce is part of the production system. Designing the AI assistant without the navigator team's participation produces an assistant the navigators do not trust and the institution cannot operate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mental-health comorbidity is common in complex episodes.** Patients receiving complex care for serious illness frequently experience anxiety, depression, and grief reactions that affect their ability to follow through on the care plan. The assistant integrates with the mental-health support pathway (recipe 11.8) for behavioral-health needs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term outcome demonstration is multi-year work.** As with the chronic-disease coach, the impact of a care coordination assistant on missed-appointment rate is observable in months; the impact on time-to-treatment for new diagnoses is observable in months to a year; the impact on readmission rate is observable in twelve to twenty-four months; the impact on cost-of-care and on hard clinical outcomes (mortality, recurrence) is observable over multiple years.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based patient access APIs are more widely deployed.** Driven by regulatory pressure (the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions, the CMS Patient Access API rule), FHIR-based patient-data-access has matured substantially since 2020. <!-- TODO: verify; the CMS Interoperability and Patient Access rule and the ONC information-blocking rule have been progressively implemented since 2020 and 2021, with continued refinement in 2024-2026 --> The data available to a care-coordination assistant via the patient's FHIR endpoints is meaningfully richer than it was five years ago.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA and the QHIN ecosystem continue to mature.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and the Qualified Health Information Networks provide mechanisms for cross-institution data exchange that are increasingly functional. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation status, QHIN designations, and operational capabilities continue to evolve; specific coverage varies --> The assistant's cross-institution integration story benefits from these developments where the participating institutions are connected.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-source synthesis well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve consolidated care plans, retrieve specific orders or referrals, retrieve appointment data, retrieve medication lists, run reconciliation comparisons, surface alert flags, schedule follow-ups, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid human-plus-AI navigation is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: AI assistant for the broad complex-episode population, with human navigator availability for high-complexity cases, escalation cases, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the AI assistant handles the routine coordination work while the human navigator focuses where their judgment is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive.** Studies of digital-plus-human care coordination programs have shown improvements in missed-appointment rates, transition-of-care follow-up rates, and patient-reported coordination experience for engaged participants, with variable effects on harder clinical outcomes. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for digital care-coordination tools and digital nurse-navigation augmentation includes studies in oncology, cardiology, post-discharge, and complex-care-management settings; specific effect sizes vary by program --> ROI demonstrations are stronger when the analysis includes downstream-event reduction (avoided readmissions, avoided ED visits, avoided treatment delays) than when the analysis focuses on direct engagement metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some episode types.** Several care-coordination vendors operate at scale for oncology navigation, post-discharge transitions, and complex-case management. Most major institutions run a hybrid: build a thin coordination-orchestration layer in-house on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with vendors for specific episode protocols, and integrate with the institution's existing case-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
